 shipbuilding has undergone major changes in response to new commercial pressures and opportunities. Early British dominance, for example, was later undermined in the 1950s by competition from the Japanese, who have since been overtaken by South Korea and, most recently, China. The case studies in this volume trace these and other important developments in the shipbuilding and ship repair industries, as well as workers' responses to these historic transformations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0https://www.aup.nl/en/publish/open-access  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aShipbuilding industryxEmployeesxHistoryy20th century. 0aShipbuilding industryxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aModern History. 7aTRANSPORTATION / Ships & Shipbuilding / General.2bisacsh  aShipbuilding.  acompetition.  aship repair.  aworkers.  aworld market.1 aAlén, José Gómez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArdeleanu, Constantin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCulkin, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFontes, Jorge, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrassa, Juliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía, Rubén Vega, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaraguchi, Takeshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeiret, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarlsson, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLinden, Marcel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMajchrzak, Sar